const_iterator
Done
string_view isn't passed by const generally.
I remember seeing the patch where you went through an removed that from the codebase and I still missed this.  I'll remove it.
Done
Add a / at the end of this.  It's unlikely that we'd ever see /redfish/v11, but there's something to be said for precision.

I can't directly add an / at the end because then I wouldn't match when the input is only "/redfish/v1" without the trailing /.

I think /redfish/v11 will already be handled by this code since immediately after this we strip "/redfish/v1" from the start of the string when creating the url struck.  That would end up being something like "1/{rest_of_uri}" and that will fail the later check of the topCollections array.

I'll at least add some test cases to confirm.  I may also change the code depending on how I address the other comments.
I added test cases to confirm that inputs like "/redfish/v11" are not accepted as valid URIs.
ACK

Is there a way to avoid this magic number and just strip the first two segments?  if not, size() works file, just declare /redfish/v1 as a constexpr string_view, then use .size() here.

Also, I'm pretty sure this constructor throws on bar URIs, so we should be using https://www.boost.org/doc/libs/1_81_0/libs/url/doc/html/url/ref/boost__urls__parse_relative_ref.html

I don't think there's a good way to strip segments at the front of a segments_ref object.  The add and remove apis are like the ones for std::vector.  I'll use your suggestions to strip them from the initial string passed to the constructor and check on what you suggested in the link.
I made the switch
ACK.  As a general rule, magic number == bad.
Note to self for the thousandth time, solve this in the core.
Does this happen in practice?  /redfish/v1 doesn't have the setupRedfishRoute call I don't think.

It does.  It calls handleServiceRootGet().  That first calls handleServiceRootHead() and that in turn calls setupRedfishRoute() https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/blob/master/redfish-core/lib/service_root.hpp#L37

No that's doing what I expect it to do.  std::lower_bound points to the element in the array such that element < target.

This initial check is just to catch the edge case where the target URI would alphabetically come before the first entry in the array. In that instance it points to the end of the array rather than an actual position. 

I'll add some comments to make it clearer.

Sorry, I meant to say this catches when the target URI is alphabetically AFTER the LAST entry in the array.

I've added a comment to clear it up.
